// CNA / CDPH Online CE - Moodle Quiz Bank (Units U01-U12 + Final; source Modules 10-17)
// Generated Moodle MVP implementation artifact. SME review required before production use.
// No PHI; fictional de-identified scenarios only.

$CATEGORY: $course$/CNA/U01

// question: CNA-U01-Q01
::CNA-U01-Q01::
What is the primary reason a nurse assistant measures and records a resident's vital signs? {
~To diagnose new medical conditions independently
=To provide objective baseline and change data the licensed nurse uses to monitor the resident
~To decide which medications the resident should receive
~To replace the need for nurse assessment
#### Nurse assistants collect and report objective data; diagnosis and medication decisions are outside the CNA scope.
}

// question: CNA-U01-Q02
::CNA-U01-Q02::
Which set best represents the four standard vital signs? {
=Temperature, pulse, respirations, blood pressure
~Height, weight, intake, output
~Pain, mood, appetite, sleep
~Pulse, oxygen tank level, room temperature, weight
#### The four standard vital signs are temperature, pulse, respirations, and blood pressure; pain is often documented as a fifth measure.
}

// question: CNA-U01-Q03
::CNA-U01-Q03::
A resident's measured value falls outside the range your facility lists as expected for that resident. What is the nurse assistant's correct action? {
~Adjust the resident's care plan
=Record the value and promptly report it to the licensed nurse
~Repeat the measurement until it reads normal
~Tell the resident not to worry
#### CNAs accurately record and promptly report out-of-range values; they do not alter care plans or hide abnormal findings.
}

// question: CNA-U01-Q04
::CNA-U01-Q04::
The term 'afebrile' most accurately means the resident\: {
~Has an elevated temperature
=Has no fever
~Has a rapid pulse
~Is dehydrated
#### Afebrile means without fever; febrile means having a fever.
}

// question: CNA-U01-Q05
::CNA-U01-Q05::
Pain is a subjective experience, so the resident's own report is the most reliable indicator of pain. {T
#### Pain is subjective; the resident's self-report is the standard, supplemented by observation when the resident cannot communicate.}

// question: CNA-U01-Q06
::CNA-U01-Q06::
Before measuring an oral temperature, which recent activity would most likely require waiting before measuring? {
~The resident watched television
=The resident drank hot coffee a few minutes ago
~The resident read a book
~The resident spoke with a visitor
#### Hot or cold liquids can alter oral temperature; waiting improves accuracy.
}

// question: CNA-U01-Q07
::CNA-U01-Q07::
Scenario\: A resident grimaces, guards one arm, and is reluctant to move during care, but says 'I'm fine.' Based on your CNA scope, what is the best action? {
~Document only the words 'I'm fine' and continue
=Note both the resident's statement and the observed nonverbal signs, and report the discrepancy to the licensed nurse
~Tell the resident they must be in pain
~Give the resident an over-the-counter pain reliever
#### Objective nonverbal signs are reportable observations; CNAs document what they see and hear and report to the nurse, and never administer medication outside scope.
}

// question: CNA-U01-Q08
::CNA-U01-Q08::
Which of the following are objective observations a nurse assistant can measure or directly observe? (Select all that apply.) {
~%50.0%Skin color and warmth
~%-50.0%The resident's medical diagnosis
~%50.0%Pulse rate
~%-50.0%The resident's stated worry about family
}

// question: CNA-U01-Q09
::CNA-U01-Q09::
Which statement about documenting vital signs is correct? {
~Record values from memory at end of shift
=Record values accurately and promptly, with the time taken
~Round values to make them look normal
~Only record values that seem abnormal
#### Accurate, timely documentation with the time of measurement supports safe care and audit-ready records.
}

// question: CNA-U01-Q10
::CNA-U01-Q10::
When a resident cannot verbally report pain, the nurse assistant should rely most on\: {
~Assuming the resident has no pain
=Observed behaviors such as facial expression, guarding, restlessness, and changes from baseline
~The resident's diagnosis only
~Waiting until the next shift
#### Behavioral and nonverbal cues, compared to the resident's baseline, guide observation and reporting when self-report is not possible.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/CNA/U02

// question: CNA-U02-Q01
::CNA-U02-Q01::
When counting a resting radial pulse, which practice best supports an accurate count? {
~Count for 5 seconds and multiply by 12
=Count for a full 30-60 seconds, noting rate, rhythm, and strength
~Count only if the resident reports feeling unwell
~Estimate based on how the resident looks
#### Counting for a longer interval and noting rhythm and strength improves accuracy, especially with irregular pulses.
}

// question: CNA-U02-Q02
::CNA-U02-Q02::
To count respirations accurately, the nurse assistant should\: {
~Tell the resident you are counting their breathing
=Count discreetly, often right after the pulse, so the resident does not consciously change breathing
~Ask the resident to breathe deeply while counting
~Count only the inhalations during exercise
#### Counting discreetly avoids voluntary changes in breathing; one rise and fall equals one respiration.
}

// question: CNA-U02-Q03
::CNA-U02-Q03::
Which finding about a resident's pulse should be reported promptly to the licensed nurse? {
~A regular rhythm at the resident's usual rate
=A new irregular rhythm or a rate well outside the resident's baseline
~The resident resting quietly
~A pulse taken after the resident sat down
#### New irregularity or a significant change from baseline is a reportable change in condition.
}

// question: CNA-U02-Q04
::CNA-U02-Q04::
A blood pressure reading is written as systolic over diastolic (for example, the top number over the bottom number). {T
#### Blood pressure is recorded as systolic/diastolic; the CNA records and reports the value to the nurse.}

// question: CNA-U02-Q05
::CNA-U02-Q05::
Which factor can falsely raise a blood pressure reading? {
~Resting quietly for several minutes first
~Using a cuff that is the correct size
=Measuring immediately after the resident hurried to the room or is anxious
~Supporting the arm at heart level
#### Recent activity and anxiety can elevate readings; correct technique reduces error.
}

// question: CNA-U02-Q06
::CNA-U02-Q06::
The term 'dyspnea' refers to\: {
~Normal easy breathing
=Difficult or labored breathing
~A slow heart rate
~High blood pressure
#### Dyspnea means difficult or labored breathing and should be reported.
}

// question: CNA-U02-Q07
::CNA-U02-Q07::
Scenario\: While taking vital signs, you notice the resident's breathing is labored and faster than usual, and their lips look slightly bluish. What is the best first action? {
~Finish all other residents' vital signs first
=Stay with the resident, ensure safety, and report the change to the licensed nurse immediately
~Wait until the next scheduled check
~Encourage the resident to walk it off
#### Labored breathing with bluish color is a potential emergency; ensure safety and report immediately. Recognizing distress and escalating is within CNA scope.
}

// question: CNA-U02-Q08
::CNA-U02-Q08::
Which actions support accurate vital sign documentation and reporting? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Record the value and the time taken
~%33.33333%Report values significantly different from baseline to the nurse
~%-100.0%Wait until end of shift to recall all numbers
~%33.33333%Use the resident's known baseline as a comparison
}

// question: CNA-U02-Q09
::CNA-U02-Q09::
A resting adult respiratory rate that is much faster than the resident's usual baseline is best described as a\: {
~Normal finding requiring no action
=Change in condition that should be reported
~Sign the resident is healthy
~Reason to stop monitoring
#### A significant change from baseline is reportable as a change in condition.
}

// question: CNA-U02-Q10
::CNA-U02-Q10::
If a resident refuses to let you take their blood pressure, the nurse assistant should\: {
~Take it anyway because it is required
=Respect the refusal, document it, and report to the licensed nurse
~Ignore the missing reading
~Tell the resident they will be discharged
#### Residents have the right to refuse; the CNA documents the refusal and reports so the nurse can follow up.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/CNA/U03

// question: CNA-U03-Q01
::CNA-U03-Q01::
A resident is on a mechanical soft diet. The nurse assistant understands this diet is intended to\: {
~Restrict all fluids
=Provide foods that are easier to chew and swallow
~Eliminate all protein
~Increase choking risk
#### A mechanical soft diet modifies texture to make chewing and swallowing safer and easier.
}

// question: CNA-U03-Q02
::CNA-U03-Q02::
Which positioning best reduces aspiration risk when assisting a resident to eat? {
~Lying flat
=Sitting upright at about 90 degrees
~Reclined far back
~Turned on the side
#### An upright position supports safe swallowing and reduces aspiration risk.
}

// question: CNA-U03-Q03
::CNA-U03-Q03::
Which observation during a meal should be reported promptly as a possible swallowing problem? {
~The resident enjoys the meal
=Coughing, choking, or a wet/gurgly voice after swallowing
~The resident drinks water
~The resident finishes the plate
#### Coughing, choking, or a wet voice can indicate dysphagia/aspiration risk and should be reported.
}

// question: CNA-U03-Q04
::CNA-U03-Q04::
Monitoring and reporting a resident's food and fluid intake is part of the nurse assistant's role. {T
#### CNAs observe, record, and report intake; the nurse uses this data for nutrition and hydration monitoring.}

// question: CNA-U03-Q05
::CNA-U03-Q05::
Which sign may indicate dehydration and should be reported? {
~Moist lips and frequent urination
=Dark concentrated urine, dry mouth, and reduced intake
~Clear urine and good appetite
~Stable weight
#### Dark urine, dry mouth, and decreased intake are warning signs of dehydration to report.
}

// question: CNA-U03-Q06
::CNA-U03-Q06::
When feeding a resident who needs assistance, the nurse assistant should\: {
~Rush so the food stays warm
=Offer small bites, allow time to chew and swallow, and avoid talking that hurries the resident
~Mix all foods together
~Feed while the resident lies down
#### Small bites and adequate time reduce choking risk and support dignity.
}

// question: CNA-U03-Q07
::CNA-U03-Q07::
Scenario\: A resident on thickened liquids asks you for a glass of regular water because they are thirsty. What is the best response? {
~Give regular water since the resident asked
=Explain you must check with the nurse, honor the prescribed thickened-liquid order, and report the request
~Ignore the request
~Tell the resident water is not allowed ever
#### Thickened-liquid orders address aspiration risk; the CNA follows the order, reports the request, and lets the nurse address it. Honoring the resident's concern with dignity matters.
}

// question: CNA-U03-Q08
::CNA-U03-Q08::
Which measures help reduce aspiration risk during meals? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Upright positioning
~%33.33333%Following the prescribed diet texture
~%-100.0%Encouraging large rapid bites
~%33.33333%Allowing time between bites
}

// question: CNA-U03-Q09
::CNA-U03-Q09::
A 'NPO' order most accurately means the resident\: {
~May eat normally
=Should have nothing by mouth
~Needs extra fluids
~Can have only liquids
#### NPO means nothing by mouth; the CNA must follow the order and report any concerns.
}

// question: CNA-U03-Q10
::CNA-U03-Q10::
A resident eats only a small portion of meals over several days. The best CNA action is to\: {
~Assume the resident is fine
=Record the intake and report the ongoing poor intake to the licensed nurse
~Force the resident to eat
~Remove the resident's meals
#### Documenting and reporting poor intake supports timely nutrition intervention by the nurse.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/CNA/U04

// question: CNA-U04-Q01
::CNA-U04-Q01::
A resident suddenly clutches their throat, cannot speak or cough, and looks panicked during a meal. This most likely indicates\: {
~Mild throat irritation
=A complete airway obstruction (severe choking) requiring immediate help
~Normal eating behavior
~A request for more food
#### Inability to speak, cough, or breathe signals a severe airway obstruction needing immediate emergency response.
}

// question: CNA-U04-Q02
::CNA-U04-Q02::
When a resident is choking but can still cough forcefully and speak, the best initial action is to\: {
~Perform abdominal thrusts immediately
=Encourage the resident to keep coughing and stay with them while monitoring
~Give the resident water
~Leave to get a snack
#### With a partial obstruction and effective cough, encourage coughing and monitor; intervene further only if it becomes severe, per facility protocol and training.
}

// question: CNA-U04-Q03
::CNA-U04-Q03::
In most facilities, the first step when you discover an emergency is to\: {
~Leave the resident to find supplies
=Call for help/activate the facility emergency response while staying with the resident
~Document the event before acting
~Move the resident to another room
#### Calling for help and not leaving the resident are priorities; documentation follows the response.
}

// question: CNA-U04-Q04
::CNA-U04-Q04::
Nurse assistants should know their facility's emergency codes and their assigned role during an emergency. {T
#### Knowing facility codes and one's role supports a safe, coordinated emergency response.}

// question: CNA-U04-Q05
::CNA-U04-Q05::
A resident is found on the floor. After ensuring the scene is safe, the nurse assistant should first\: {
~Lift the resident back to bed alone
=Call for the nurse/help and avoid moving the resident until assessed, unless in immediate danger
~Give the resident something to drink
~Document and continue other duties
#### Do not move a fallen resident before assessment unless immediate danger exists; call for the nurse to assess for injury.
}

// question: CNA-U04-Q06
::CNA-U04-Q06::
Which is an example of a general safety measure that helps prevent emergencies in long-term care? {
~Leaving spills on the floor
=Keeping call lights within reach and clearing walkways of hazards
~Blocking exits with equipment
~Ignoring frayed cords
#### Accessible call lights and clear, hazard-free walkways reduce falls and other emergencies.
}

// question: CNA-U04-Q07
::CNA-U04-Q07::
Scenario\: During a fire alarm (facility 'Code Red'), you are with a resident who uses a wheelchair. What is the best action consistent with CNA scope and typical RACE principles? {
~Use the elevator to evacuate quickly
=Follow facility fire procedure\: ensure resident safety, contain/close doors as trained, and follow staff direction for evacuation
~Run to safety first and return later
~Open all windows
#### Facility fire response (often summarized as Rescue, Alarm, Contain, Extinguish/Evacuate) prioritizes resident safety; elevators are typically not used in a fire.
}

// question: CNA-U04-Q08
::CNA-U04-Q08::
Which signs in a resident warrant immediate help and reporting as possible distress? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Sudden chest discomfort
~%33.33333%Sudden inability to breathe or speak
~%-100.0%Resting comfortably
~%33.33333%New confusion or unresponsiveness
}

// question: CNA-U04-Q09
::CNA-U04-Q09::
After an emergency is over, the nurse assistant's documentation should\: {
~Include guesses about the cause
=Objectively record what was observed, the time, and actions taken, then report to the nurse
~Be skipped to save time
~Blame the resident
#### Documentation should be objective, timely, and factual, supporting an audit-ready record.
}

// question: CNA-U04-Q10
::CNA-U04-Q10::
The main reason a nurse assistant should not exceed their training during an emergency is that\: {
~It saves time
=Acting outside trained scope can harm the resident and is not within CNA responsibilities
~The nurse prefers it
~It looks better on records
#### Staying within trained scope protects residents; CNAs summon licensed help for actions beyond their role.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/CNA/U05

// question: CNA-U05-Q01
::CNA-U05-Q01::
Which statement about normal aging is most accurate? {
~Confusion is a normal, expected part of aging
=Some slowing of body systems is normal, but sudden confusion is not normal and should be reported
~Aging always means total dependence
~Older adults cannot learn new routines
#### Gradual changes occur with aging, but acute confusion is a change in condition to report, not 'just aging.'
}

// question: CNA-U05-Q02
::CNA-U05-Q02::
As skin changes with age, residents are at higher risk for\: {
~Faster wound healing
=Skin breakdown and pressure injuries
~Thicker, tougher skin
~No change in skin
#### Aging skin is thinner and more fragile, increasing risk of breakdown and pressure injuries.
}

// question: CNA-U05-Q03
::CNA-U05-Q03::
Which observation about a resident's skin should be reported promptly? {
~Intact, warm, dry skin
=A new reddened area over a bony prominence that does not fade
~Normal skin color
~Clean, moisturized skin
#### Non-blanching redness over a bony area is an early pressure injury sign to report.
}

// question: CNA-U05-Q04
::CNA-U05-Q04::
Repositioning and good skin care help prevent pressure injuries in residents with limited mobility. {T
#### Regular repositioning, skin care, and pressure relief are core prevention measures.}

// question: CNA-U05-Q05
::CNA-U05-Q05::
A resident with reduced mobility is most at risk for which set of complications without preventive care? {
=Pressure injuries, stiffness/contractures, and constipation
~Improved circulation
~Stronger muscles
~Better appetite
#### Immobility increases risk for pressure injuries, contractures, constipation, and other complications.
}

// question: CNA-U05-Q06
::CNA-U05-Q06::
Which approach best supports a resident with a chronic condition such as arthritis during care? {
~Move the resident quickly to finish faster
=Allow extra time, use gentle movements, and respect reports of pain
~Ignore stiffness
~Tell the resident pain is not real
#### Gentle, paced care and respecting pain reports support comfort and dignity.
}

// question: CNA-U05-Q07
::CNA-U05-Q07::
Scenario\: A resident who is normally alert becomes suddenly drowsy and confused during your shift. What is the best action? {
~Assume it is normal aging and continue
=Report the sudden change to the licensed nurse promptly and monitor the resident's safety
~Let the resident sleep and say nothing
~Wait until the next day to mention it
#### Sudden mental status change is a reportable change in condition that may signal an acute problem.
}

// question: CNA-U05-Q08
::CNA-U05-Q08::
Which are reportable changes in a long-term care resident? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%New shortness of breath
~%33.33333%Sudden change in mental status
~%-100.0%Stable usual routine
~%33.33333%New skin breakdown
}

// question: CNA-U05-Q09
::CNA-U05-Q09::
Promoting resident independence in activities of daily living means the nurse assistant should\: {
~Do everything for the resident
=Encourage and allow the resident to do what they safely can, assisting only as needed
~Discourage the resident from trying
~Rush the resident
#### Supporting safe independence maintains function and dignity.
}

// question: CNA-U05-Q10
::CNA-U05-Q10::
Which body system change is commonly associated with aging? {
~Increased bladder capacity
=Decreased bone density, raising fracture risk
~Faster reflexes
~Improved night vision
#### Decreased bone density (and slower reflexes, vision changes) commonly accompany aging and raise injury risk.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/CNA/U06

// question: CNA-U06-Q01
::CNA-U06-Q01::
When communicating with a resident who has dementia and is confused, the best approach is to\: {
~Argue with the resident until they agree
=Use a calm voice, simple words, and reassurance, approaching from the front
~Speak quickly and use medical terms
~Ignore the resident
#### Calm, simple, reassuring communication and approaching from the front reduce fear and agitation.
}

// question: CNA-U06-Q02
::CNA-U06-Q02::
A resident with dementia becomes agitated during bathing. A dementia-sensitive response is to\: {
~Continue quickly to get it over with
=Stop, reassure, identify possible triggers, and try again later or adjust the approach
~Tell the resident to calm down
~Restrain the resident
#### Recognizing triggers and using a calm, flexible approach respects the resident and reduces distress; restraints are not appropriate.
}

// question: CNA-U06-Q03
::CNA-U06-Q03::
Which behavior is a common, expected challenge when caring for residents with dementia? {
~Perfect memory of recent events
=Memory loss, confusion about time/place, and possible repetition
~No change in behavior
~Always independent in all ADLs
#### Memory loss, disorientation, and repetition are common with dementia and call for patience and structure.
}

// question: CNA-U06-Q04
::CNA-U06-Q04::
Maintaining familiar routines and a calm environment can help reduce confusion and agitation for residents with dementia. {T
#### Consistency and a calm environment support residents with dementia.}

// question: CNA-U06-Q05
::CNA-U06-Q05::
Psychosocial needs of long-term care residents include\: {
~Only physical care
=Social connection, dignity, meaningful activity, and respect for preferences
~Isolation
~Ignoring cultural background
#### Psychosocial care addresses social, emotional, cultural, and dignity needs, not just physical tasks.
}

// question: CNA-U06-Q06
::CNA-U06-Q06::
A resident frequently tries to leave the unit looking for a long-deceased spouse. A dementia-sensitive, dignity-preserving response is to\: {
~Bluntly tell the resident the spouse is dead repeatedly
=Respond with gentle reassurance and redirection, and report wandering/exit-seeking to the nurse for safety planning
~Lock the resident in their room
~Ignore the behavior
#### Gentle reassurance, redirection, and reporting for safety planning are appropriate; harsh repeated correction and improper confinement are not.
}

// question: CNA-U06-Q07
::CNA-U06-Q07::
Which actions support the psychosocial well-being of residents? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Respecting personal and cultural preferences
~%33.33333%Encouraging participation in activities they enjoy
~%-100.0%Talking about residents disrespectfully
~%33.33333%Honoring privacy and dignity
}

// question: CNA-U06-Q08
::CNA-U06-Q08::
Community resources and family involvement are important for residents because they\: {
~Replace professional care
=Support emotional well-being, identity, and connection beyond the facility
~Are not allowed in long-term care
~Increase confusion
#### Family and community connections support identity and emotional well-being.
}

// question: CNA-U06-Q09
::CNA-U06-Q09::
When a resident with dementia gives an answer that is not factually accurate but is not causing harm, the best general approach is to\: {
~Always correct them firmly
=Avoid unnecessary confrontation, provide reassurance, and redirect when needed
~Laugh at the resident
~Report them for lying
#### Avoiding needless confrontation and using reassurance/redirection preserves dignity and reduces distress.
}

// question: CNA-U06-Q10
::CNA-U06-Q10::
A nurse assistant notices a normally social resident has withdrawn and stopped attending activities. The best action is to\: {
~Ignore it as a personal choice
=Report the change to the licensed nurse, as withdrawal can signal illness, depression, or another problem
~Force the resident to attend
~Tell the resident to cheer up
#### A change in social engagement is a reportable observation that may indicate an underlying issue.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/CNA/U07

// question: CNA-U07-Q01
::CNA-U07-Q01::
The main goal of restorative/rehabilitative nursing care is to\: {
~Do all tasks for the resident permanently
=Help the resident regain or maintain the highest possible level of function and independence
~Speed up care by skipping exercises
~Discourage movement
#### Restorative care promotes and maintains function and independence to the resident's highest practicable level.
}

// question: CNA-U07-Q02
::CNA-U07-Q02::
Range-of-motion (ROM) exercises help prevent\: {
=Joint stiffness and contractures
~Faster healing of wounds
~Weight gain
~Improved appetite
#### ROM helps maintain joint mobility and prevent contractures in residents with limited movement.
}

// question: CNA-U07-Q03
::CNA-U07-Q03::
While assisting a resident with prescribed exercises, the nurse assistant should\: {
~Push the joint past the point of pain
=Move joints gently and stop if the resident reports pain, then report it
~Skip the exercises if inconvenient
~Force rapid movements
#### Movements should be gentle and within comfort; pain should stop the activity and be reported.
}

// question: CNA-U07-Q04
::CNA-U07-Q04::
Encouraging a resident to do as much of their own self-care as safely possible is part of restorative care. {T
#### Promoting self-care within safe limits supports the resident's function and dignity.}

// question: CNA-U07-Q05
::CNA-U07-Q05::
When a resident uses a walker, the nurse assistant supports safety by\: {
~Letting the resident hurry
=Ensuring the walker is within reach, brakes/feet are intact, and the path is clear
~Removing the walker during transfers
~Placing the walker far away
#### Proper device readiness and a clear path reduce falls and support mobility.
}

// question: CNA-U07-Q06
::CNA-U07-Q06::
Why is consistency important when carrying out a resident's restorative program? {
~It is not important
=Regular, consistent practice helps maintain gains and prevent decline
~It saves the facility money only
~It allows skipping documentation
#### Consistency supports maintenance of function; gains can be lost without regular practice.
}

// question: CNA-U07-Q07
::CNA-U07-Q07::
Scenario\: A resident in a restorative walking program says they are too tired today and feels dizzy. What is the best action? {
~Insist they walk the full distance anyway
=Stop the activity, ensure the resident's safety, and report the dizziness and fatigue to the nurse
~Tell the resident dizziness is normal and continue
~Document that the resident walked the full program
#### Dizziness is a safety concern; stop, keep the resident safe, and report. Never falsify documentation.
}

// question: CNA-U07-Q08
::CNA-U07-Q08::
Which practices support restorative care goals? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Encouraging safe self-care
~%33.33333%Following the prescribed restorative plan
~%-100.0%Doing everything for the resident to save time
~%33.33333%Reporting changes in the resident's ability
}

// question: CNA-U07-Q09
::CNA-U07-Q09::
A resident regains the ability to feed themselves with a special utensil. The nurse assistant should\: {
~Take over feeding to be faster
=Encourage and allow the resident to self-feed and report the progress
~Hide the utensil
~Tell the resident not to bother
#### Supporting newly regained skills and reporting progress reinforces restorative outcomes.
}

// question: CNA-U07-Q10
::CNA-U07-Q10::
Proper body mechanics during transfers protect\: {
~Only the resident
=Both the resident and the nurse assistant from injury
~Only the nurse assistant
~Neither person
#### Good body mechanics and approved transfer techniques protect both resident and caregiver.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/CNA/U08

// question: CNA-U08-Q01
::CNA-U08-Q01::
Which is an example of an OBJECTIVE observation? {
~The resident seems sad
=The resident's skin is warm and reddened over the left heel
~The resident is probably in pain
~The resident might be hungry
#### Objective observations are measurable or directly observed facts; the others are interpretations or assumptions.
}

// question: CNA-U08-Q02
::CNA-U08-Q02::
Which is an example of SUBJECTIVE information? {
~Pulse of a measured rate
=The resident states, 'My stomach hurts.'
~Reddened skin
~A measured temperature
#### Subjective information is what the resident reports; it is recorded as the resident's own statement.
}

// question: CNA-U08-Q03
::CNA-U08-Q03::
When reporting an observation to the licensed nurse, the nurse assistant should provide\: {
~Only a vague summary
=Specific, factual, and timely information about what was observed
~An opinion about the diagnosis
~Information only if asked
#### Specific, factual, timely reporting helps the nurse respond appropriately.
}

// question: CNA-U08-Q04
::CNA-U08-Q04::
Nurse assistants should report changes in a resident's condition promptly rather than waiting until the end of the shift. {T
#### Prompt reporting allows timely intervention and is safer for the resident.}

// question: CNA-U08-Q05
::CNA-U08-Q05::
Which set are all senses a nurse assistant uses to make observations? {
=Sight, hearing, smell, and touch
~Only sight
~Only hearing
~Taste of the resident's food
#### Observation uses sight, hearing, smell, and touch; tasting a resident's food is not an appropriate observation method.
}

// question: CNA-U08-Q06
::CNA-U08-Q06::
Which observation is the highest priority to report immediately? {
~A resident requesting a different TV channel
=A resident with new chest discomfort and shortness of breath
~A resident who wants a snack
~A resident reading quietly
#### New chest discomfort with shortness of breath is urgent and requires immediate reporting.
}

// question: CNA-U08-Q07
::CNA-U08-Q07::
Scenario\: You observe a resident's output appears darker and reduced, the resident's lips are dry, and they seem more confused than usual. What should you report? {
~Only that the resident is confused
=All three objective observations together, with the time, to the licensed nurse
~Nothing, since one symptom alone is minor
~Your guess that it is a urinary infection
#### Reporting the full picture of objective observations (not a diagnosis) helps the nurse assess possible dehydration or other issues.
}

// question: CNA-U08-Q08
::CNA-U08-Q08::
Which are objective observations a CNA can chart? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Amount of meal eaten
~%33.33333%Resident's measured weight
~%-100.0%Your opinion of the resident's prognosis
~%33.33333%Visible swelling of the ankle
}

// question: CNA-U08-Q09
::CNA-U08-Q09::
Why is the timing of an observation important in reporting? {
~It is not important
=Knowing when a change occurred helps the nurse evaluate the situation
~It makes the chart longer
~It is only needed for billing
#### Time context helps the clinical team interpret changes and respond.
}

// question: CNA-U08-Q10
::CNA-U08-Q10::
If a nurse assistant is unsure whether an observation is important enough to report, the best action is to\: {
~Decide not to report it
=Report it to the licensed nurse and let the nurse determine significance
~Wait to see if it gets worse
~Ask another resident
#### When in doubt, report; the licensed nurse determines clinical significance.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/CNA/U09

// question: CNA-U09-Q01
::CNA-U09-Q01::
Which statement about charting/documentation is correct for a nurse assistant? {
~Document care before it is performed
=Document accurately, promptly, and only the care actually given and observations actually made
~Document what you think should have happened
~Leave documentation for the next shift to complete
#### Documentation must be accurate, timely, and truthful, reflecting only actual care and observations.
}

// question: CNA-U09-Q02
::CNA-U09-Q02::
If a nurse assistant makes an error while charting on paper, the correct method is to\: {
~Erase or use correction fluid
=Draw a single line through the error, write the correction, and initial/date per facility policy
~Scribble it out completely
~Rewrite the whole page
#### A single line through the error preserves the original record and supports an audit-ready, legal document.
}

// question: CNA-U09-Q03
::CNA-U09-Q03::
The resident's medical record is a legal document, and entries should never be falsified. {T
#### The record is a legal document; falsification is prohibited and can harm residents and lead to discipline.}

// question: CNA-U09-Q04
::CNA-U09-Q04::
Which entry is documented appropriately and objectively? {
~'Resident was difficult and rude.'
='Resident ate 50% of lunch and walked to the dining room with a walker.'
~'Resident is probably depressed.'
~'Resident seemed fine, I think.'
#### Objective, specific, factual entries are appropriate; labels and assumptions are not.
}

// question: CNA-U09-Q05
::CNA-U09-Q05::
When should a nurse assistant chart care that was provided? {
~Days later
=As soon as possible after the care is given, per facility policy
~Only at annual review
~Never
#### Timely charting near the time of care improves accuracy and reliability of the record.
}

// question: CNA-U09-Q06
::CNA-U09-Q06::
Confidentiality of the resident's record means the nurse assistant should\: {
~Share resident details with anyone who asks
=Access and share resident information only as needed for care and only with authorized people
~Post about residents on social media
~Discuss residents in the elevator
#### Resident information is private; access and disclosure are limited to care needs and authorized individuals.
}

// question: CNA-U09-Q07
::CNA-U09-Q07::
Scenario\: You realize you forgot to chart a completed care task from earlier in your shift. The best action is to\: {
~Leave it out since time passed
=Make a late entry per facility policy, clearly noted as a late entry with the correct date/time of care
~Ask a coworker to chart it as if they did it
~Backdate the entry to hide the delay
#### A properly labeled late entry maintains an honest, audit-ready record; backdating or having others chart your care is falsification.
}

// question: CNA-U09-Q08
::CNA-U09-Q08::
Which are features of legally sound documentation? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Accurate and factual entries
~%33.33333%Timely entries
~%-100.0%Whiteout used to remove errors
~%33.33333%Confidential handling of records
}

// question: CNA-U09-Q09
::CNA-U09-Q09::
A change in a resident's condition should be documented and\: {
~Kept secret
=Reported to the licensed nurse, with the report and time noted
~Mentioned only to family
~Posted publicly
#### Changes must be both documented and reported to the nurse, with the time recorded.
}

// question: CNA-U09-Q10
::CNA-U09-Q10::
Using only approved abbreviations and clear language in charting helps to\: {
~Confuse other staff
=Ensure the record is understood correctly and reduce errors
~Make the chart look complicated
~Hide information
#### Approved abbreviations and clear language improve communication and reduce errors.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/CNA/U10

// question: CNA-U10-Q01
::CNA-U10-Q01::
Which statement best reflects culturally and individually sensitive end-of-life care? {
~All residents grieve and want the same care
=Respect each resident's and family's individual, cultural, and spiritual preferences
~Avoid discussing the resident's wishes
~Impose the caregiver's own beliefs
#### End-of-life care is individualized and respects cultural and spiritual preferences.
}

// question: CNA-U10-Q02
::CNA-U10-Q02::
The main goal of hospice/comfort care is to\: {
~Cure the underlying illness
=Provide comfort, dignity, and symptom relief near the end of life
~Speed up the dying process
~Stop all care
#### Hospice/comfort care focuses on comfort, dignity, and quality of life rather than cure.
}

// question: CNA-U10-Q03
::CNA-U10-Q03::
When providing comfort to a dying resident, a nurse assistant should\: {
~Avoid the room to give space
=Provide gentle care, presence, mouth and skin care, and report symptoms of discomfort to the nurse
~Talk loudly to keep them awake
~Withhold repositioning
#### Comfort care includes gentle physical care, presence, and reporting discomfort for management by the nurse.
}

// question: CNA-U10-Q04
::CNA-U10-Q04::
Grief is a normal response, and residents, families, and staff may all experience it. {T
#### Grief is a normal process experienced by residents, families, and caregivers.}

// question: CNA-U10-Q05
::CNA-U10-Q05::
An advance directive (such as a documented care wish) means the nurse assistant should\: {
~Ignore it
=Be aware of it and follow the care team's direction consistent with the resident's documented wishes
~Decide for the resident
~Tell the family to override it
#### Advance directives express the resident's wishes; the care team follows them, and CNAs support care accordingly.
}

// question: CNA-U10-Q06
::CNA-U10-Q06::
Postmortem care performed by a nurse assistant should be done\: {
~Carelessly since the resident has died
=With the same respect and dignity given in life, following facility policy and the nurse's direction
~Without privacy
~Before confirming the death per policy
#### Postmortem care is performed respectfully, with privacy, per policy and the nurse's direction, after death is pronounced per facility process.
}

// question: CNA-U10-Q07
::CNA-U10-Q07::
Scenario\: The family of a dying resident is tearful and asks you medical questions about how long their loved one has to live. The best response is to\: {
~Give your own estimate of time remaining
=Offer compassionate presence and support, and refer their medical questions to the licensed nurse
~Tell them not to be upset
~Change the subject and leave
#### Prognosis questions are answered by licensed clinicians; the CNA provides compassionate support and refers clinical questions appropriately.
}

// question: CNA-U10-Q08
::CNA-U10-Q08::
Which are appropriate comfort measures for a dying resident? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Gentle mouth and skin care
~%33.33333%Calm, quiet, respectful presence
~%-100.0%Ignoring signs of pain
~%33.33333%Repositioning for comfort as tolerated
}

// question: CNA-U10-Q09
::CNA-U10-Q09::
If a nurse assistant feels emotionally affected after a resident's death, a healthy response is to\: {
~Suppress all feelings and never discuss them
=Acknowledge the feelings and use appropriate support resources
~Avoid all future residents
~Quit immediately
#### Acknowledging grief and using support resources promotes caregiver well-being.
}

// question: CNA-U10-Q10
::CNA-U10-Q10::
Maintaining a resident's dignity during the dying process includes\: {
~Discussing the resident loudly in the hallway
=Providing privacy, gentle communication, and respecting personal and cultural wishes
~Rushing care
~Excluding the family
#### Dignity is maintained through privacy, respectful communication, and honoring wishes.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/CNA/U11

// question: CNA-U11-Q01
::CNA-U11-Q01::
Residents in long-term care have the right to\: {
=Be free from abuse, neglect, and mistreatment
~Be restrained for staff convenience
~Have their mail read by staff
~Be denied participation in their own care
#### Residents have the right to be free from abuse, neglect, exploitation, and mistreatment.
}

// question: CNA-U11-Q02
::CNA-U11-Q02::
Which is an example of physical abuse? {
~Helping a resident transfer safely
=Hitting, slapping, or rough handling of a resident
~Offering a snack
~Listening to the resident
#### Physical abuse includes hitting, slapping, or rough handling that causes harm or pain.
}

// question: CNA-U11-Q03
::CNA-U11-Q03::
Which is an example of neglect? {
~Promptly answering call lights
=Failing to provide needed food, hydration, hygiene, or care
~Repositioning a resident on schedule
~Reporting a change in condition
#### Neglect is the failure to provide needed care or services that results in or risks harm.
}

// question: CNA-U11-Q04
::CNA-U11-Q04::
Verbal threats, intimidation, and humiliation are forms of emotional/psychological abuse. {T
#### Emotional/psychological abuse includes threats, intimidation, humiliation, and isolation.}

// question: CNA-U11-Q05
::CNA-U11-Q05::
Which is an example of financial exploitation? {
~Helping a resident call their bank with consent and authorization
=Taking or misusing a resident's money or belongings without authorization
~Returning found property to a resident
~Documenting personal items on admission
#### Financial exploitation is the unauthorized or improper use of a resident's funds or property.
}

// question: CNA-U11-Q06
::CNA-U11-Q06::
Which set are possible warning signs of abuse that should be reported? {
=Unexplained bruises, fear of a specific person, and sudden withdrawal
~Good appetite and social engagement
~Stable mood and clean environment
~Participation in activities
#### Unexplained injuries, fearfulness, and behavior changes can indicate abuse and must be reported.
}

// question: CNA-U11-Q07
::CNA-U11-Q07::
Scenario\: You see a coworker roughly grab a resident's arm and speak harshly, and the resident appears frightened. What should you do? {
~Ignore it because it is not your resident
=Ensure the resident's immediate safety and report the suspected abuse per facility policy and law
~Confront the coworker later privately and keep it between you
~Wait to see if it happens again
#### Suspected abuse must be reported promptly per policy and law; protecting the resident comes first. (Specific reporting timelines/recipients require SME/legal confirmation for the facility's jurisdiction.)
}

// question: CNA-U11-Q08
::CNA-U11-Q08::
Which actions help prevent abuse and protect residents? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Treating residents with respect and dignity
~%33.33333%Reporting suspected abuse promptly
~%-100.0%Using restraints for convenience
~%33.33333%Following person-centered, trauma-informed care
}

// question: CNA-U11-Q09
::CNA-U11-Q09::
Using a physical restraint on a resident for staff convenience or discipline is\: {
~Acceptable when busy
=Prohibited; restraints are not used for convenience or discipline
~A good prevention tool
~Required nightly
#### Restraints for convenience or discipline are prohibited and can constitute abuse.
}

// question: CNA-U11-Q10
::CNA-U11-Q10::
Involuntary seclusion (isolating a resident against their will) is best classified as\: {
~A normal care routine
=A form of resident mistreatment that must be reported
~A reward system
~An activity choice
#### Involuntary seclusion is a form of mistreatment and is reportable.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/CNA/U12

// question: CNA-U12-Q01
::CNA-U12-Q01::
As a mandated reporter, when a nurse assistant suspects resident abuse, they must\: {
~Wait for proof before doing anything
=Report the suspicion promptly per facility policy and applicable law
~Investigate fully on their own first
~Report only if a supervisor agrees
#### Mandated reporters report reasonable suspicion promptly; proof is not required, and the duty is personal. (Jurisdiction-specific timelines/recipients require SME/legal confirmation.)
}

// question: CNA-U12-Q02
::CNA-U12-Q02::
The duty to report suspected abuse generally means the nurse assistant\: {
~Can delegate the duty and forget it
=Has a personal responsibility to ensure a report is made, even if others are also reporting
~Only reports if asked
~Reports only at year end
#### The reporting duty is personal; the CNA must ensure a report is made per law and policy.
}

// question: CNA-U12-Q03
::CNA-U12-Q03::
Resident information related to an abuse report should still be handled confidentially and shared only with authorized parties. {T
#### Confidentiality applies; information is shared only with authorized investigators/authorities as required.}

// question: CNA-U12-Q04
::CNA-U12-Q04::
Good-faith reporting of suspected abuse generally means a mandated reporter\: {
~Will always be punished
=Is reporting an honest, reasonable suspicion and is generally protected for doing so
~Must guarantee the abuse occurred
~Should stay anonymous and never follow up
#### Good-faith reports based on reasonable suspicion are generally protected; reporters need not prove the abuse. (Confirm jurisdiction protections with SME/legal.)
}

// question: CNA-U12-Q05
::CNA-U12-Q05::
When documenting an observation related to suspected abuse, the nurse assistant should record\: {
~Personal opinions and blame
=Objective, factual observations (what was seen/heard), the time, and actions taken
~Only a vague note
~Nothing, to avoid involvement
#### Objective, factual, timely documentation supports investigation and an audit-ready record.
}

// question: CNA-U12-Q06
::CNA-U12-Q06::
Confidentiality of resident information generally means a nurse assistant should NOT\: {
~Discuss care with the assigned nurse
=Post or discuss resident information publicly or on social media
~Document care in the record
~Report changes to the nurse
#### Public disclosure or social media posting of resident information violates confidentiality.
}

// question: CNA-U12-Q07
::CNA-U12-Q07::
Scenario\: A resident quietly tells you that a family member took money from them and threatened them, and begs you not to tell anyone. What is the best action? {
~Promise to keep it completely secret
=Reassure the resident, keep them safe, and report the suspected exploitation/abuse per policy and law, explaining you must report to protect them
~Decide it is a family matter and do nothing
~Confront the family member yourself
#### Suspected exploitation must be reported; the CNA cannot promise secrecy that conflicts with the duty to protect and report. (Confirm jurisdiction process with SME/legal.)
}

// question: CNA-U12-Q08
::CNA-U12-Q08::
Which are appropriate steps when abuse is suspected? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Ensure the resident's immediate safety
~%33.33333%Report per facility policy and law
~%33.33333%Document objective observations
~%-100.0%Hide the information to avoid conflict
}

// question: CNA-U12-Q09
::CNA-U12-Q09::
If a nurse assistant fears retaliation for reporting suspected abuse, they should\: {
~Not report at all
=Still report, knowing reporting is required and retaliation against good-faith reporters is generally prohibited
~Wait until they leave the job
~Report anonymously to a resident
#### The duty to report stands; protections generally exist against retaliation for good-faith reports. (Confirm with SME/legal.)
}

// question: CNA-U12-Q10
::CNA-U12-Q10::
The overall purpose of abuse prevention, recognition, and reporting training is to\: {
~Increase paperwork
=Protect residents' safety, dignity, and rights
~Reduce resident rights
~Replace the licensed nurse's role
#### The goal is to protect residents' safety, dignity, and rights through prevention, recognition, and reporting.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/CNA/FINAL

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q01
::CNA-FINAL-Q01::
The nurse assistant's primary role in vital signs is to\: {
~Diagnose conditions
=Accurately measure, record, and report data to the licensed nurse
~Prescribe treatment
~Change the care plan
#### CNAs collect and report data within scope; diagnosis and care-plan changes are not CNA functions.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q02
::CNA-FINAL-Q02::
The four standard vital signs are temperature, pulse, respirations, and\: {
~Weight
=Blood pressure
~Height
~Appetite
#### Blood pressure completes the four standard vital signs.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q03
::CNA-FINAL-Q03::
A resident's self-report is the most reliable indicator of their pain. {T
#### Pain is subjective; self-report is the standard.}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q04
::CNA-FINAL-Q04::
'Dyspnea' means\: {
~Slow pulse
=Difficult or labored breathing
~Normal breathing
~High temperature
#### Dyspnea is labored breathing.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q05
::CNA-FINAL-Q05::
Counting respirations discreetly is important because\: {
~It is faster
=Awareness can cause the resident to change their breathing
~It is required by law
~It improves pulse accuracy
#### Discreet counting avoids voluntary changes.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q06
::CNA-FINAL-Q06::
A mechanical soft diet is intended to\: {
~Restrict fluids
=Make chewing and swallowing easier and safer
~Remove all protein
~Increase choking risk
#### Texture-modified diets aid safe swallowing.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q07
::CNA-FINAL-Q07::
The safest position for assisting a resident to eat is\: {
~Lying flat
=Upright at about 90 degrees
~Reclined far back
~On the side
#### Upright positioning reduces aspiration risk.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q08
::CNA-FINAL-Q08::
Coughing, choking, or a wet/gurgly voice during meals may indicate\: {
~Good appetite
=A swallowing problem to report
~Normal eating
~Dehydration only
#### These are possible dysphagia/aspiration signs to report.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q09
::CNA-FINAL-Q09::
Dark concentrated urine, dry mouth, and reduced intake may indicate\: {
~Overhydration
=Dehydration
~Good nutrition
~Normal aging only
#### These are warning signs of dehydration.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q10
::CNA-FINAL-Q10::
'NPO' means\: {
~Eat normally
=Nothing by mouth
~Only liquids
~Extra fluids
#### NPO \= nothing by mouth.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q11
::CNA-FINAL-Q11::
A resident who cannot speak, cough, or breathe is showing signs of\: {
~A partial obstruction
=A severe (complete) airway obstruction needing immediate help
~Normal eating
~Mild irritation
#### These signs indicate severe choking requiring immediate response.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q12
::CNA-FINAL-Q12::
The first step on discovering an emergency is usually to\: {
~Document first
=Call for help/activate emergency response and stay with the resident
~Move the resident
~Leave to find supplies
#### Summon help and remain with the resident.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q13
::CNA-FINAL-Q13::
A fallen resident should generally not be moved before assessment unless they are in immediate danger. {T
#### Avoid moving a fallen resident before nurse assessment unless danger exists.}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q14
::CNA-FINAL-Q14::
Elevators are typically NOT used during which emergency? {
~A medication delivery
=A fire
~A meal service
~A family visit
#### Elevators are generally not used during a fire.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q15
::CNA-FINAL-Q15::
A sudden change in a resident's mental status should be\: {
~Ignored as normal aging
=Reported promptly to the licensed nurse
~Documented only at year end
~Discussed with visitors
#### Acute mental status change is a reportable change in condition.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q16
::CNA-FINAL-Q16::
A new, non-fading reddened area over a bony prominence is an early sign of\: {
~Improved circulation
=A pressure injury
~Dehydration
~Normal skin
#### Non-blanching redness over bone is an early pressure injury sign.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q17
::CNA-FINAL-Q17::
Repositioning residents with limited mobility primarily helps prevent\: {
=Pressure injuries
~Weight gain
~Better hearing
~Faster speech
#### Regular repositioning helps prevent pressure injuries.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q18
::CNA-FINAL-Q18::
Dementia-sensitive communication includes\: {
~Arguing until the resident agrees
=Calm voice, simple words, reassurance, approaching from the front
~Speaking fast with medical jargon
~Ignoring the resident
#### Calm, simple, reassuring communication helps.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q19
::CNA-FINAL-Q19::
A dignity-preserving response to a resident with dementia who is exit-seeking is to\: {
~Lock them in a room
=Use gentle reassurance and redirection and report for safety planning
~Argue with them repeatedly
~Ignore it
#### Reassurance, redirection, and reporting support safety and dignity.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q20
::CNA-FINAL-Q20::
Which support residents' psychosocial well-being? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Respecting cultural preferences
~%33.33333%Encouraging enjoyed activities
~%-100.0%Talking about residents disrespectfully
~%33.33333%Honoring privacy and dignity
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q21
::CNA-FINAL-Q21::
The goal of restorative care is to\: {
~Make the resident fully dependent
=Help the resident reach/maintain the highest practicable function
~Skip exercises
~Discourage movement
#### Restorative care maximizes function and independence.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q22
::CNA-FINAL-Q22::
Range-of-motion exercises help prevent\: {
=Contractures and joint stiffness
~Weight gain
~Better appetite
~Faster healing
#### ROM prevents contractures and maintains mobility.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q23
::CNA-FINAL-Q23::
During assisted exercise, if the resident reports pain, the nurse assistant should\: {
~Push past the pain
=Stop and report the pain
~Speed up
~Ignore it
#### Stop the activity and report pain.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q24
::CNA-FINAL-Q24::
Good body mechanics during transfers protect both the resident and the nurse assistant. {T
#### Proper technique protects both people.}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q25
::CNA-FINAL-Q25::
Which is an objective observation? {
~The resident seems anxious
=The resident's measured pulse rate
~The resident is probably hungry
~The resident might be in pain
#### A measured pulse rate is objective.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q26
::CNA-FINAL-Q26::
Which is subjective information? {
~A measured temperature
='My head hurts,' stated by the resident
~Reddened skin
~Counted respirations
#### A resident statement is subjective.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q27
::CNA-FINAL-Q27::
To correct a paper charting error, the nurse assistant should\: {
~Use correction fluid
=Draw a single line through it, correct, and initial/date
~Erase it
~Rewrite the page
#### Single line, correction, initial/date preserves the legal record.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q28
::CNA-FINAL-Q28::
The medical record is a legal document and must never be falsified. {T
#### Records are legal documents; falsification is prohibited.}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q29
::CNA-FINAL-Q29::
When in doubt about whether to report an observation, the nurse assistant should\: {
~Not report it
=Report it and let the nurse judge significance
~Wait until it worsens
~Ask a visitor
#### When in doubt, report.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q30
::CNA-FINAL-Q30::
Charting should be completed\: {
~Days later
=As soon as possible after care, per policy
~Only annually
~Never
#### Timely charting improves accuracy.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q31
::CNA-FINAL-Q31::
Hospice/comfort care focuses on\: {
~Curing the illness
=Comfort, dignity, and symptom relief
~Speeding death
~Stopping all care
#### Comfort care emphasizes comfort and dignity.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q32
::CNA-FINAL-Q32::
Culturally sensitive end-of-life care means\: {
~Treating all residents identically
=Respecting individual, cultural, and spiritual preferences
~Imposing the caregiver's beliefs
~Avoiding the topic
#### Care is individualized to the resident's culture and beliefs.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q33
::CNA-FINAL-Q33::
Postmortem care should be performed\: {
~Carelessly
=With the same respect and dignity given in life, per policy
~Without privacy
~Without the nurse's direction in all cases
#### Postmortem care is respectful and follows policy/nurse direction.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q34
::CNA-FINAL-Q34::
Grief is a normal response that residents, families, and staff may all experience. {T
#### Grief is normal across all involved.}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q35
::CNA-FINAL-Q35::
If a family asks the nurse assistant a prognosis question (how long), the best response is to\: {
~Give your own estimate
=Provide support and refer the clinical question to the nurse
~Tell them not to ask
~Leave the room
#### Prognosis is answered by licensed clinicians; CNA gives support.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q36
::CNA-FINAL-Q36::
Residents have the right to be free from\: {
~Activities
=Abuse, neglect, and mistreatment
~Visitors
~Their own care plan
#### Residents have the right to be free from abuse, neglect, and mistreatment.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q37
::CNA-FINAL-Q37::
Failing to provide needed food, hygiene, or care is\: {
~Good practice
=Neglect
~Restorative care
~A resident right
#### Withholding needed care is neglect.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q38
::CNA-FINAL-Q38::
Threats, intimidation, and humiliation are forms of\: {
~Physical abuse
=Emotional/psychological abuse
~Good care
~Financial abuse
#### These are emotional/psychological abuse.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q39
::CNA-FINAL-Q39::
Taking a resident's money without authorization is\: {
=Financial exploitation
~Physical abuse
~Neglect
~Acceptable if small
#### Unauthorized use of funds is financial exploitation.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q40
::CNA-FINAL-Q40::
As a mandated reporter, the nurse assistant must report suspected abuse\: {
~Only with proof
=Promptly, based on reasonable suspicion, per law and policy
~Only if a supervisor agrees
~At year end
#### Reasonable suspicion triggers prompt reporting; proof is not required.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q41
::CNA-FINAL-Q41::
Using physical restraints for staff convenience or discipline is prohibited. {T
#### Restraints for convenience/discipline are prohibited.}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q42
::CNA-FINAL-Q42::
Good-faith reporting of suspected abuse generally means the reporter\: {
~Must prove the abuse
=Reports an honest, reasonable suspicion and is generally protected
~Will be punished
~Should never follow up
#### Good-faith reports are generally protected.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q43
::CNA-FINAL-Q43::
Which are reportable changes in condition? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%New shortness of breath
~%33.33333%Sudden confusion
~%-100.0%Stable usual routine
~%33.33333%New skin breakdown
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q44
::CNA-FINAL-Q44::
This online CE course, by itself\: {
~Completes all California CNA renewal requirements
=Does not by itself complete all CNA renewal requirements; it provides online CE only with no clinical hours
~Replaces clinical competency validation
~Grants certification
#### The course is online CE only; it does not include clinical hours or competency validation and does not by itself satisfy all renewal requirements.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q45
::CNA-FINAL-Q45::
Resident confidentiality means a nurse assistant should\: {
~Share information publicly
=Limit access and disclosure to care needs and authorized people
~Post about residents online
~Discuss residents in public areas
#### Confidential information is shared only as needed for care with authorized parties.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q46
::CNA-FINAL-Q46::
A resident refuses a measurement or care. The nurse assistant should\: {
~Force the care
=Respect the refusal, document it, and report to the nurse
~Ignore it
~Discharge the resident
#### Residents may refuse; document and report.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q47
::CNA-FINAL-Q47::
Scenario\: A resident is eating when they suddenly cannot speak or cough and clutch their throat. Within your training, you should\: {
~Wait and watch quietly
=Call for help immediately and respond per your facility's choking/emergency protocol and your training
~Offer water
~Document and continue with other residents
#### Severe choking is an emergency\: call for help and respond per protocol and training.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q48
::CNA-FINAL-Q48::
Scenario\: You notice unexplained bruising on a resident and they flinch when a particular staff member enters. The best action is to\: {
~Assume it is from normal activity
=Ensure the resident's safety, document objective observations, and report suspected abuse per policy and law
~Ask the resident to keep it quiet
~Wait to see if it recurs
#### Possible abuse signs require safety, objective documentation, and reporting. (Confirm jurisdiction process with SME/legal.)
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q49
::CNA-FINAL-Q49::
Which is the best example of person-centered care? {
~Doing tasks the fastest way regardless of preference
=Tailoring care to the resident's needs, preferences, and dignity
~Treating all residents identically
~Excluding residents from decisions
#### Person-centered care respects individual needs, preferences, and dignity.
}

// question: CNA-FINAL-Q50
::CNA-FINAL-Q50::
The nurse assistant's documentation should always be\: {
~Based on assumptions
=Objective, accurate, timely, and confidential
~Completed by another shift
~Optional
#### Documentation must be objective, accurate, timely, and confidential.
}

